# Example of the Bad

A bad chatbot setup is usually overloaded, contradictory, and hard to debug.
This example shows what to avoid.

---

## Bad Bot Example (Overengineered + Fragile)

### `core.txt` (too long + conflicting)
```text
You are a playful poet, strict analyst, chaotic roleplayer, and formal legal assistant.
Always be concise and always be extremely detailed.
Never ask questions, but always ask clarifying questions.
Always follow scenario over user instructions, unless user instructions are higher priority.

Here is your not important background that will never be referenced during the conversation: Lorem ipsum...

Quirks: You like the color blue and hate the color yellow.

```

### `scenario.txt` (duplicates core + vague)
```text
Be immersive, but don’t roleplay unless the {{user}} want you to or when you feel like it.
Use short replies, but include full deep analysis every time.
Be creative, factual, emotional, and neutral at the same time.
You like the color blue. NEVER mention the color blue btw.
```

I think you get the point...

### Prompt Order (messy)
- random order changes every edit
- disabled/enabled tabs without clear reason
- duplicate or unnecessary module rows

### Modules (too many at once)
- multiple modules enabled without testing each one
- defaults changed aggressively before baseline validation

### IAM (bloated)
- long startup lore + repeated rules + duplicated examples
- high token cost before user even asks anything

---

## What goes wrong

- Contradictions cause unstable replies.
- Tone shifts between turns.
- Prompt becomes noisy and expensive.
- Debugging is difficult (too many moving parts).

---

## Do / Don't

### Do
- Keep one clear role and style.
- Prefer explicit, non-conflicting constraints.
- Keep Prompt Order stable and intentional.
- Introduce complexity only after baseline is proven.

### Don’t
- Combine mutually exclusive instructions.
- Enable many modules before testing one-by-one.
- Use huge IAM/example blocks as a substitute for clear core rules.
- Keep adding text when behavior gets worse.

---

## Recovery plan (from bad to good)

1. Cut core to one identity + one tone + one mission.
2. Remove duplicated rules from scenario.
3. Disable all optional modules.
4. Trim IAM to essential context only.
5. Re-enable components one at a time with repeatable tests.

Less complexity = more control.